On #WorldEnvironmentDay, I am excited to be an ambassador for the Queens Green Canopy. If you can put up with me flapping my jaw for a couple of minutes - watch the video to find out about a tree planting campaign on a big scale. It aims to get people from all around the UK planting trees but if you're not from the UK, get planting in your own country! Head to @queensgreencanopy for more info! 

#queensgreencanopy #plantatreeforthejubilee

node.text:
Back in September I shot for a film called 'Kimana Tuskers' following some very special elephants. Here's the trailer... 

'There are fewer than 20 tuskers left on earth, where ivory still sweeps the ground. Filmed throughout the Greater Amboseli ecosystem in Kenya, Kimana Tuskers is a short film of epic proportions. Follow the famous tusker known as Craig, and the younger elephant bulls who entrust their lives to him as they navigate a vanishing landscape through the Kimana Wildlife Corridor. This is the passage of experience, a brotherhood, built on respect, trust and loyalty, and what awaits them is the promised land, so that one day their sons will rise to be kings…'

Written & directed by Jamie Joseph, produced by @Saving_the_Wild, and narrated by two-time Academy Nominated actor @Djimon_Hounsou. Post production by Academy Award Winning facility Park Road Post.

For updates to screening locations visit KimanaTuskers.org - US tour slated for Sept/Oct.

#KimanaTuskers

node.text:
A couple of years ago I spent 6 weeks living on a sailboat for a @natgeo series ‘Wild_Life: Resurrection Island’. We went to document the unbelievable wildlife that lives on the sub Antarctic island of South Georgia. Critical to this project was our fearless sailboat captain @kirstenggr – navigating the world’s roughest oceans, often single handed, is what she does best! She’s actually now preparing to race around the world solo sailing with no technology (no GPS... nothing!!!). Kirsten and I are going to be chatting about our adventure in a webinar on Friday May 8th at 5pm UK time, 12pm ET, 9am PT. Topics will include - How do you solve a boat problem in the middle of nowhere? How do you get a wildlife expedition like this commissioned? Who empties Barry my vomit bucket? 
And this comes with the added bonus that all proceeds from the talk go to a small non-profit helping people in need during this crisis. You must register ahead of the time to be able to watch it – link in my profile. Thanks so much and hopefully see some of you there!

node.text: @connorstefanison on the sea ice off  Hudson Bay. We’d just gone live to @natgeo ‘s social media accounts on satellite internet (via the magic of the little unit on that yellow box). What we’d forgotten is that after ending the live broadcast, we needed to wait for a higher resolution version of the video to upload. Meanwhile the tide changed, the ice shifted and water started coming up around the box. Fortunately, the upload completed just in time for Connor to grab the box and run away to safer ice! #wildlife #ice #snow #arctic

node.text: A grey wolf in a snowstorm on the west coast of the Hudson Bay, Canada. We humans have done terrible things to wolves. It’s estimated that in 1600, there were 2 million wolves in North America. Due to 400 years of systematic extermination, there are now just 80,000. There is hope though, they are on the comeback but they still need us to stop persecuting them. These top predators keep herbivore populations in check allowing countless other species to thrive. Our mislead cultural fear of wolves is regularly exploited to justify predator killing contests – one of the many barriers to their comeback. @filipe_deandrade and @brianmoghari are doing some great and shocking work on these contests. #wildlife #animals #wolves #wolf #snow #canada #frozen

node.text: A female harp seal pops up through a breathing hole in the ice in the Gulf of St Lawrence, Canada. Above the surface on a piece of ice nearby, she has a tiny 5-day-old pup. Each day the ice changes dramatically as tides and ocean currents breakup and reform the packing. Even so, this female is able to navigate with unbelievable precision to re-find her pup. #seal #arctic #cold #snow #ice

node.text: A large male polar bear heading out on to the sea ice to hunt. Like many polar bears, this male had spent the summer on land, waiting for the sea to re freeze. We met him in late Autumn on the western Hudson Bay. Over a period of just a few days the sea went from a wavy liquid to a rock solid ice pathway for the bears. At sunset, we witnessed this bear head out on to the ice in search of seals to get his first good meal in 4 months. #wildlife #animals #bears #polar #ice #arctic #seaice

node.text: A harp seal mother and pup in the Gulf of St Lawrence, Quebec, Canada. This species has an extraordinary breeding cycle. Females give birth to pups on moving ice floes. They suckle the pup for just 10 to 14 days. During the last few days of this short period, they encourage the pup into the water to help them learn to swim. After the swimming lessons, they abandon the pup. The females then mate with the males who have been waiting nearby before heading north to their feeding grounds. #wildlife #animals #harpseal #polar #ice #arctic #seal #cute

node.text: Polar bears can weigh more than 700kg/1600lbs. This presents a potential problem when hunting seals on thin ice. Their solution- massive paws. Their paws can be 12 inches wide spreading their weight. Their rough foot pads and short, sharp claws also give them extra traction. #wildlife #animals #ice #snow #bear #polarbear

node.text:
Every autumn, the Hudson Bay in Canada undergoes a dramatic change. In the space of just a few days, the ocean turns into a rock-solid ice pathway. This event is hotly anticipated by polar bears - the ice allows them to hunt their primary prey, the ringed seal. Sunrise during this time is always magical as wild temperature fluctuations create spooky mist that rises off the newly formed ice!
#bear #arctic #cold #snow #polarbear #wild_life #wildlife

These tiny polar bear cubs wouldn’t let their mother sleep! Unlike other species of bear in North America, male polar bears do not den in winter time. Female polar bears however den during the winter to give birth to cubs. This particular family belongs to a special population. Female polar bears that den near the Hudson Bay go through one of the longest fasting periods of any mammal. As the sea ice (their hunting ground) melts around July, they come on to land. In September/October they head further in land to build a den. In February/March, they break out the den with their new cubs. They then head out onto the 
sea (which has frozen solid over the winter) to hunt seals. So for the 8 months they are on land, the mother must go without a good meal even while she is pregnant and suckling new cubs. As this fasting period is pushing the bears to their limit, any increase in Arctic temperature and therefore an increase in the ice-free period will have dramatic consequences on the female’s ability to raise new cubs. #wildlife #animals #bears #polar #ice #arctic #cuteanimals

node.text: A harp seal pup on an ice floe in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, Quebec, Canada. This pup had just finished a big milk meal. Harp seal mothers suckle their pups for just 10 to 14 days. They then abandon the pups and head north leaving the pup to fend for itself. #wildlife #harpseal #polar #seal #cute
